\section{Purpose}


The purpose of this report is to document the changes made in the
serial and parallel implementations of the Floyd-Warshall algorithm
from that proposed. Furthermore, this report is to analyze the
performance of the parallel implementation in comparison the serial
implementation.


\section{Design}



\subsection{Modules}

The design called for the following modules:

\begin{itemize}
\item util.h - matrix manipulation and I/O
\item floyd.h - contains the serial and parallel implementations of
  the Floyd-Warshall Aglorithm

\item main.c - the general running of the algorithm 
\item test.h - a test suite to verify correctness

\end{itemize}


\subsection{Serial}

The most notable departure from the initial design of the algorithm
was the inclusion of the transposed matrix as an attempted
optimization.  The decision was made to forgo the implementation due
to time constraints, a minimal projected margin of performance
benefit, as well as the scope of this project as a focus on
parallelization.  

Aside from this, other differences in the design included the
replacement of function arguments as global variables (i.e. the number
of nodes in the graph).  Otherwise, the implementation of the serial
algorithm was straightforward and required few additional
considerations beyond the triple loop.


\subsection{Parallel}

The parallel implementation differed from the proposed implementation
mainly in the blocking mechanism used to force the main threads to
wait for the completion of all working threads at the end of each
$k$th.  The proposed implementation of this included a switch variable
which in which bits were masked on to signify that a corresponding
thread.  Another proposed version of this was to use a pthread
condition variable.  I decided against this because of the
unreliability of the approach.  Therefore, I used a mutex to protect
the critical section of each of the thread loops.  The final algorithm
which controlled the threads' flow was as follows.


Each thread will follow these steps
\begin{enumerate}

\item exit thread if the $k$th row is complete

\item check variable \emph{go} to see if the $k$th iteration is ready

\item 'checkout' a range of rows based on a predefined amount of rows.  This locks a mutex specific to the thread and signifies that the thread is in the critical section, i.e. still working

\item iterate and perform the inner-most loop on each row allocated to the thread

\item 'checkin' the thread, unlocks the thread's mutex

\item loop back to step 1

\end{enumerate}

Therefore, the main loop's purpose was to ready the system for
the $k$th iteration:

\begin{enumerate}
\item read in adjacency matrix

\item initialize N\_THREADS threads (cli specified)

\item create all threads 

\item let each thread check out a range of threads (cli specified)

\item attempt to lock the mutex for each thread.  This prevents them
  from passing through their 'checkout' phase

\item increment $k$ and set the \emph{go} signal to true (1)

\item unlock the mutex on each thread to allow them to checkout rows

\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Parallel Hang-Ups}


The main difficulty in implementing the parallel version of the
algorithm was in blocking the threads while minimizing any possible
bottleneck. By distributing the control mechanism to each thread
(which owns a mutex of its own) I was able to control the program's
flow while minimizing contention over a specific resource.  

With this design, another unforeseen difficulty was getting the
threads to exit properly.  This became an issue when multiple calls to
the parallel algorithm encountered a sparsity of thread resources.
The solution was to guarantee that the threads exit upon completion
before requesting a new block of rows and wait on a locked mutex while
main loop terminated.

\section{Testing}

A unit/composite test suit is provided alongside the code. The input
function is tested by comparing a matrix read in from a file to a
hard-coded matrix.  I used a function to allocate and duplicate a
matrix.  This is also tested on the hard-coded sample matrix. The
correctness of the serial version of the algorithm was tested against
two hand computed shortest path matrices. The parallel version was
tested against the same matrices with 4 allotted threads. The
remainder of the tests were performed by generating random adjacency
matrices and comparing the shortest path matrices of the serial and
parallel versions for varying thread counts and problem sizes.  Each
of the parallel tests were run 200 times to account for the
possibility of any non-deterministic behavior.

A sample output of the test suite is as follows:
\lang{bash}
\begin{code}
  TEST: [                    test_input] [            tests/sample1.mtrx]  PASSED
  TEST: [                     test_copy] [                              ]  PASSED
  TEST: [                   test_serial] [            tests/output1.mtrx]  PASSED
  TEST: [           test_parallel x 200] [            tests/output1.mtrx]  PASSED
  TEST: [                   test_serial] [            tests/output3.mtrx]  PASSED
  TEST: [           test_parallel x 200] [            tests/output3.mtrx]  PASSED
  TEST: [         random parallel x 200] [          n = 9, n_threads = 4]  PASSED
  TEST: [         random parallel x 200] [         n = 10, n_threads = 4]  PASSED
  TEST: [         random parallel x 200] [         n = 43, n_threads = 4]  PASSED
  TEST: [         random parallel x 200] [         n = 9, n_threads = 11]  PASSED
  TEST: [         random parallel x 200] [        n = 10, n_threads = 11]  PASSED
  ...
\end{code}


\section{Experimental Setup}

The testing space of interest to this project included testing
algorithm performance for a range of thread counts over a range of
problem sizes.  The thread counts tested were $T = \{2, 4, 8, 16,
64\}$ (where the number of threads represents the total number of
threads, including the main loop).  The problem sizes tested were $N =
\{16, 32, 64, 128, 256, 512, 1024\}$. Furthermore, the parallel
implementation of the algorithm allowed for an adjustable block size,
such that each thread claims a given number of block sizes at once.
This allows for fine tuning to optimize the work load while
considering the overhead from an increased number of accesses to the
'work-pile.'  The block sizes tested were $B = \{1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32,
64, 128, 512\}$

Therefore the parallel experimental space consisted of 3 degrees of freedom over 
\al{
  \text{Test Space} = S = T \times N \times B, ~~ | S| = 441 \text{  tests}
}

The experiment was carried out by submitting the battery of tests to a
16 core workstation using AMD Opteron 4386 processors.  For
each test the wall-clock execution time was recorded.

The parallel timing includes the creation and joining of all of its
threads.


\section{Experimental Results}

A complete and likely unnecessary table of numerical results is
included in Appendix A.

The graphs presented in this section present the data for the optimal
choice in row block size.

The first general result is a comparison of the overhead introduced to
the parallel implementation with a single thread.  See
Figure~\ref{overhead}.

\figH {../plots/overhead.png}
      {Overhead comparison of single-thread parallel and serial versions}
      {overhead}{.9} 

The second important result is a direct comparison of the execution
times of the threaded version on different problem sizes.
Figure~\ref{size} shows each problem size when run with varying thread
counts.  For comparison, the serial computation execution time is
included for a 1024 node file size.

\figH {../plots/parallel_size.png}
      {Comparison of single-thread parallel and serial execution times}
      {size}{.9} 

Figure~\ref{perf} displays the parallel execution time in terms of speedup over the serial version where 

\al{
 \text{Speedup} = \frac{ \text{Execution Time}_{serial} }{ \text{Execution Time}_{parallel}}
}

\figH {../plots/parallel_performance.png}
      {Overhead comparison of single-thread parallel and serial versions}
      {perf}{.9} 


